## Object oriented ##
You could use an object oriented approach and create a class for a box, e. g.

    public class Box {

    private int x;
    private int y;
    private int z;

    public Box(int x, int y, int z) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
        this.z = z;
    }

    public int getVolume() {
        return x * y * z;
    }

    /**
     * Rotates this box 90 degree around x-axis.
     */
    public void rotateX() {
        int temp = y;
        y = z;
        z = temp;
    }

    /**
     * Rotates this box 90 degree around y-axis.
     */
    public void rotateY() {
        int temp = x;
        x = z;
        z = temp;
    }

    /**
     * Rotates this box 90 degree around z-axis.
     */
    public void rotateZ() {
        int temp = x;
        x = y;
        y = temp;
    }

    public boolean fitsIn(Box otherBox) {
        return this.x &lt;= otherBox.x
                &amp;&amp; this.y &lt;= otherBox.y
                &amp;&amp; this.z &lt;= otherBox.z;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return String.format(&quot;(%d, %d, %d)&quot;, x, y, z);
    }
}

Then you could rotate the smaller box (smaller by volume) in each of the 6 possible positions and check if it fits.

## Using collections ##
Another approach is to check if for each value of one box, there is a greater or equal value on the other box. As you can rotate the box the order of the values is not important.
Given the values for each box are in a list, you could use a method like this:

    public static boolean isFitting(List&lt;Integer&gt; box1Values, List&lt;Integer&gt; box2Values) {
        Integer max1;
        Integer max2;

        while (!box1Values.isEmpty()) {
            max1 = Collections.max(box1Values);
            max2 = Collections.max(box2Values);

            if (max1 &gt; max2) {
                return false;
            }

            box1Values.remove(max1);
            box2Values.remove(max2);
        }

        return true;
    }

